WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
Welcome to The Test Set. Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:11.040
in statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning. Dig into what makes

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:17.400
them tick, plus the insights, experiments, and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:22.240
In this episode, we talk with Mike Bostock, creator of the visualization library D3, one

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.040
of the top three starred GitHub repos through much of the 2010s. He was graphics editor

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:31.559
at the New York Times, and he founded Observable, whose Reactive Notebooks handle the whole

00:00:31.559 --> 00:00:36.119
of his process from end to end. We talk about his journey into visualization, which was

00:00:36.119 --> 00:00:40.540
heavily influenced by his early time on the Google search quality team, where feature

00:00:40.540 --> 00:00:45.680
decisions often came down to a single number that was heavily debated, and how notebooks

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.080
are sort of an attempt to crack open all the computation that goes into visualization.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:55.840
And of course, we end talking about AI agents and the future of notebooks. I'm so excited

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:59.919
to bring this interview to folks. And so with that, Mike Bostock.

00:00:59.919 --> 00:01:05.680
All right, Mike, welcome to The Test Set. We're so excited to have you on. So you're

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:13.519
Mike Bostock, creator of D3, and you were the graphics editor at New York Times, and

00:01:13.519 --> 00:01:19.120
now a founder at Observable, where you build powerful tools for visualizing data through

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:23.480
code, UI, and AI. Yeah, thank you so much for coming on.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.279
It's my pleasure. It's great to be here.

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:32.839
And I'm joined by co-hosts, Hadley Wickham, who's chief scientist at Posit, and Isabel,

00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:38.919
who's just an incredible software engineer at Posit, and graciously agreed to come. Yeah.

00:01:38.919 --> 00:01:46.019
As people can see, especially the people listening via podcast, we're in beautiful San Francisco.

00:01:46.019 --> 00:01:50.760
If you can't see the video, we're actually on the Golden Gate Bridge, and we're surrounded

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:55.760
by birds. It's a beautiful day. So we're so happy to have you.

00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:03.120
Mike, I feel like you've done so much. And as I talk to colleagues about D3, I feel like

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:10.720
there's this incredible history of D3. So I'd love to talk a bit about how you got there

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:16.279
and built D3. And then I know there's a lot you've talked about on open source and AI

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:21.479
and your work with Observable. I was curious if you could just catch us up a bit on some

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:26.279
of the history of D3 and your work there. Sure. I do like to build tools and have been

00:02:26.279 --> 00:02:33.039
doing it for a while. And I think a lot of my ideas for tools come out of frustrations

00:02:33.039 --> 00:02:38.839
using existing tools, or in some ways a desire to understand how those existing tools are

00:02:38.839 --> 00:02:44.880
built or why they were built the way they were built. For D3 specifically, I was doing

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:53.279
a lot of work in browsers, in SVG, using JavaScript, using the DOM API. And in particular,

00:02:53.279 --> 00:02:59.759
the DOM API is very verbose. And if you're doing stuff with SVG, there's this namespace

00:02:59.759 --> 00:03:07.080
URL that you have to remember to create an SVG element or to set xlink href attribute

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:11.800
and stuff like that. And so it was just difficult to remember this specific URL. I mean, I remember

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.600
it now because I've repeated it so many times. And just to zoom way out, D3, you're making

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:22.199
like beautiful visualizations in SVG. Is that? Yeah. So the goal with D3, I mean, and there

00:03:22.199 --> 00:03:27.000
are other libraries that I worked on that kind of predate that. But I think D3 specifically

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.440
was focused on kind of interaction and animation and transitions and performance. And I think

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:37.520
in many ways, like a lot of its success came out of being at the right place in the right

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:43.440
time kind of thing. So it really builds on web standards. So these standards exist already

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:49.240
or existed already, SVG and Canvas, and of course, the DOM API, as I mentioned. But in

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:55.520
many ways, they were very tedious to use. And so the goal for D3 was to build on those

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:59.600
technologies, like let you leverage all of those capabilities, but make it much easier

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:05.119
for you to get started, make it much more, you know, performant, I guess, like maintain

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:10.000
that performance capabilities, but make it easier for you to use it. There's also an

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.160
element to D3 that's about kind of all of the visualization techniques and just kind

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:21.040
of packaging those up in a reusable way. So like the tree map, squarified tree map algorithm,

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:25.480
for example, like that's fairly tedious to write yourself, like to read the paper and

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:31.079
to implement it yourself. And there were some existing implementations of that that predate

00:04:31.079 --> 00:04:35.519
D3. But what I wanted to do with D3 is to try to think about like, what is the kind

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:41.279
of purest encapsulation of that algorithm in a way that's independent of how you display

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:47.359
it. So like the layout algorithms in D3 are all like data space. They're just like data

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:52.399
in data out. They don't dictate how you display it, like whether you're using SVG or Canvas

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:56.720
or WebGL or anything else, or even like React, whatever you want to do. So I want to try

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:03.079
to like decompose it into these composable pieces. So that, and I think that helps contribute

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:04.079
to its longevity.

00:05:04.079 --> 00:05:08.640
I mean, maybe you had the same experience as me. It's like reading these viz papers

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:13.279
would be like a cool visualization. And they provide software, but the software does that

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:16.920
visualization and like nothing else. And then you're like, well, I'd like to combine it

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:21.359
with this other visualization. And there's just like no like connection.

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:25.200
And they're really fun to work on as well. Like the circle packing algorithm, I think

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.880
has been the most fun one that I worked on. And they have these like fun diagrams that

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:34.119
show how they work, how they kind of build out these layouts progressively. And you can

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:39.000
kind of work on them and you get these really satisfying animations as it's iterating over

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.679
the layout. And yeah, like packaging them up so that it's easy for people to reuse that's

00:05:43.679 --> 00:05:51.559
not tied to like any implementation artifact that's in a paper has all of these kind of

00:05:51.559 --> 00:05:56.320
somewhat arbitrary choices of what language it's in, or what other kind of parameters

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:01.519
or UI that's around it. And so it is fun as a kind of a software engineering puzzle to

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:07.480
think about like, what is the most reusable version of this implementation? And in a way

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:12.320
like that is kind of the art of open source is like, how do you take a complex problem

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:17.160
and kind of pare it down to its essence so that people can then use your solution or

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:20.600
use your tool in as many cases as possible.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:24.720
You talked about this a little bit in your lessons from like 10 years of open source

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:30.519
too, but there's also that like, this is like a hard problem and I've solved it and it feels

00:06:30.519 --> 00:06:35.839
very satisfying. And then sometimes you're like, well, like, was this actually a problem

00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:39.799
that needed to be solved? Or like, does this actually like move the needle? Like, do you

00:06:39.799 --> 00:06:43.200
like, how do you like some of the, there's definitely the aspect of like, this is a fun

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:47.720
challenge and I've like nailed it and like, Oh, I've done something useful. And those

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.480
are like, sometimes totally.

00:06:49.959 --> 00:06:55.160
Sure. Yeah. I mean, I think you want to have both your intrinsic motivation and your extrinsic

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:59.399
motivation. So I think it's definitely fun to work on stuff that you just enjoy. Like

00:06:59.399 --> 00:07:03.320
if there's an interesting puzzle of you, like implementing this algorithm, like, and great,

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:07.200
like just do that. And I think a lot of that's kind of the beauty of open source is that

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:11.279
you can work a lot of these things that are, you're just intrinsically motivated to work

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:17.359
on. And then if other people find it useful, now you have an extrinsic motivation to like

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:21.679
continue to develop it, right? Because you've got this community, you've got this user

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:25.720
base, they're excited about it as well. And they're giving you ideas of what it can do

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:30.399
next or ways that you can make it easier to use. So that's good, you know, validation.

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:36.399
And you, I'm really curious in terms of the open source, would you sort of like set the

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:42.920
stage? Because I know you did like proto-viz, I think before D3, like, what was it like

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:48.239
basically? How did you get into viz? What was it like sort of starting with proto-viz

00:07:48.239 --> 00:07:51.160
and open source? What was that experience like?

00:07:51.279 --> 00:07:58.119
Sure. Well, getting into viz happened much earlier. So I think the first time I really

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:04.200
got interested in visualization in a professional capacity, I was working at Google and I was

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:09.959
in the search quality evaluation team. And the evals team is, their job is to kind of

00:08:09.959 --> 00:08:13.440
take all of these experiments that the search quality team is doing, like these potential

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:19.920
changes to ranking or like new signals that can be incorporated and try to empirically

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:25.320
assess, you know, what the impact will be, like, is this improving quality or not? And at

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:30.399
the time, you know, the main outcome of these evals was a number, you know, a number

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:35.760
between one and five. And the idea is like, if your experiment scored like 4.1 or higher,

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:39.119
you know, you got to launch. And if it was lower than that, then you had to go back and

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:44.200
kind of make some improvements. And the problem was, you know, as is always the case,

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:48.679
like there's human opinions and personalities involved. And every time you're working on

00:08:48.679 --> 00:08:53.880
some change to ranking or whatever, like there are certain things that you're trying to

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:58.520
do and maybe other things that you're not thinking about so much. And I found that a

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:03.119
lot of the discussions around whether we should launch something or not could devolve

00:09:03.119 --> 00:09:07.200
into like debating whether the eval metric was good, like, or whether it didn't kind of

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:10.280
sufficiently capture the unique nature of this experiment.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:11.400
This one number.

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:15.799
Yeah, yeah. You're just arguing over a number. And it's like, well, this, you know, the

00:09:15.799 --> 00:09:19.400
argument was more about the evals being flawed than the kind of the nature of the

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:24.239
experiment. So what I was interested in is like, how can we surface all of this information

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:29.599
that we're collecting about these experiments? So some of it was, you know, kind of a, b,

00:09:29.599 --> 00:09:32.479
whatever, you can do, you can do experiments where you actually launch it and you see what

00:09:32.599 --> 00:09:34.919
the effect is on real human users.

00:09:34.919 --> 00:09:39.760
But we would also do stuff with human readers where we have sort of test sets or query

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:43.280
test sets. And we would kind of ask them, like, is this improving the quality?

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:45.599
Like, is this a better result for this query?

00:09:45.599 --> 00:09:47.479
Is this a better result set for this query?

00:09:47.732 --> 00:09:54.732
And so we had all of this information, and by surfacing that information, partly through visualization...

00:09:54.409 --> 00:10:00.169
I think we helped the engineers better understand what the impact of their changes was, and

00:10:00.169 --> 00:10:05.009
then they could spend more time actually debating that, right, and highlight maybe some of the

00:10:05.009 --> 00:10:08.009
unexpected consequences of their experiments.

00:10:09.024 --> 00:10:11.944
And this is, this is like 2003-ish?

00:10:12.064 --> 00:10:16.824
Um, yeah, so I think 2005, 2006, something like that.

00:10:16.924 --> 00:10:20.124
Are you, in this case, are you using like JavaScript since —

00:10:20.304 --> 00:10:21.264
Java, actually.

00:10:22.264 --> 00:10:26.064
Although I did start getting into some web-based — I think one of the first

00:10:26.064 --> 00:10:30.184
things I did was using XSLT, which is really going to date me, but there was

00:10:30.184 --> 00:10:36.544
this cool like XML transformation style sheet kind of thing, and you could, yeah,

00:10:36.544 --> 00:10:39.724
I guess we would generate like XML outputs from the data and then like

00:10:39.724 --> 00:10:43.224
transform them into a webpage, and so it was another way of doing it.

00:10:43.283 --> 00:10:47.024
But yeah, I think some of the first visualizations that I did were actually

00:10:47.024 --> 00:10:53.963
in Java, um, and yeah, I didn't get into kind of the JavaScript — well, so

00:10:53.963 --> 00:10:55.604
actually, no, I should correct myself.

00:10:56.064 --> 00:11:04.943
In 1999, I was like, I did a summer internships, a kind of a Netscape, um,

00:11:05.044 --> 00:11:07.084
and I wrote for their developer website.

00:11:07.123 --> 00:11:10.123
So there is actually — not even 1999, I think it's actually

00:11:10.123 --> 00:11:12.204
like 1998 or something like that.

00:11:12.564 --> 00:11:17.443
I wrote a, my first JavaScript visualization library, um, like

00:11:17.443 --> 00:11:20.884
pre-Canvas, pre-SVG, pre-everything.

00:11:21.123 --> 00:11:25.884
It could only like render a table element, and it had to use like an

00:11:25.884 --> 00:11:29.964
invisible one-by-one — it actually had three one-by-one GIFs.

00:11:30.263 --> 00:11:33.964
There was like a transparent one, a blue one, and a red one.

00:11:34.704 --> 00:11:39.903
And you just did like horrible things using just the HTML table element, and

00:11:39.903 --> 00:11:42.184
it could produce, I think, only a bar chart.

00:11:42.424 --> 00:11:45.244
Are you saying it's like, it's like a grid?

00:11:45.303 --> 00:11:49.064
It just made a grid and now it's filling it in with red and blue and transparent?

00:11:49.064 --> 00:11:54.504
Like, cause there wasn't even — there was very difficult to do graphics

00:11:54.744 --> 00:11:57.184
in the browser in that time.

00:11:57.663 --> 00:12:01.663
And so you, but you could kind of approximate, um, exact pixel

00:12:01.663 --> 00:12:04.204
positioning by using the table element.

00:12:04.964 --> 00:12:10.004
Um, and so I did terrible things in order to produce these very rudimentary bar charts.

00:12:10.004 --> 00:12:13.163
But yeah, I think that, you know, I've, so I've always had an interest in, in

00:12:13.163 --> 00:12:17.643
helping people understand data through visualization and the talk technology

00:12:17.643 --> 00:12:20.884
was not really there at the time, but you know, 20 years later or something,

00:12:20.884 --> 00:12:22.443
it's, it's really quite impressive.

00:12:22.684 --> 00:12:23.044
Yeah.

00:12:23.044 --> 00:12:23.844
It's so interesting.

00:12:23.884 --> 00:12:28.563
I mean, even you described a little bit like SVG, even at a little time later

00:12:28.563 --> 00:12:32.783
being tricky to use too, but probably less tricky than a table with

00:12:32.783 --> 00:12:36.904
like three one-by-one, uh, images in it.

00:12:36.904 --> 00:12:37.423
For sure.

00:12:37.464 --> 00:12:41.384
And I think, you know, it's not in a sense, like a flaw in the design.

00:12:41.384 --> 00:12:46.863
I think like it's, it's really helpful to have these, um, kind of formal and

00:12:46.904 --> 00:12:52.063
very precise, um, APIs that you can then build whatever you want on top of it.

00:12:52.544 --> 00:12:57.703
Um, so, you know, D3 is obviously a very opinionated way and a specialized

00:12:57.703 --> 00:12:59.404
way of constructing the DOM.

00:12:59.404 --> 00:13:02.003
And so it's not in a sense, like better than the DOM API.

00:13:02.003 --> 00:13:06.764
It's just, it's much more specialized, focused on how do you transform the

00:13:06.764 --> 00:13:09.363
DOM to conform to a particular data set?

00:13:09.884 --> 00:13:12.044
How do you describe transformations to the DOM?

00:13:12.884 --> 00:13:17.244
Um, and so I think, you know, what my interest, I guess, is in this more.

00:13:18.223 --> 00:13:19.443
It's, I guess it's design, right?

00:13:19.443 --> 00:13:24.223
It's like, how do you create software interfaces that are more accessible to

00:13:24.223 --> 00:13:27.803
humans, that they can understand how to use them effectively and use them

00:13:27.803 --> 00:13:28.363
efficiently?

00:13:28.684 --> 00:13:28.964
Yeah.

00:13:29.363 --> 00:13:34.563
And going from, you know, tables and then SVGs and all of this, do you feel like

00:13:34.563 --> 00:13:37.404
there's something that you wish you had learned way at the beginning that would

00:13:37.404 --> 00:13:39.443
have made this entire experience better?

00:13:39.604 --> 00:13:41.964
Or is it just the nature of changing software?

00:13:43.163 --> 00:13:46.083
I mean, I, I'm sure I've learned lots of things along the way.

00:13:46.124 --> 00:13:52.244
I think maybe one of the biggest lessons from D3 is kind of the value of the

00:13:52.264 --> 00:13:59.624
ecosystem, like the web standards, like I mentioned, um, you know, this ability to

00:13:59.624 --> 00:14:03.863
interoperate and be compatible with and use the tool in conjunction with all of

00:14:03.863 --> 00:14:04.703
these other tools.

00:14:05.143 --> 00:14:10.503
So when we wrote the D3 paper, I think in some ways it was controversial, um, because

00:14:10.503 --> 00:14:12.384
it was coming after the Protoviz paper.

00:14:13.063 --> 00:14:16.744
And in a way it was rejecting a bunch of the ideas from Protoviz.

00:14:17.283 --> 00:14:23.643
Um, and I think one of the things that was heretical about it was this idea that, you

00:14:23.643 --> 00:14:27.203
know, you don't need a specialized representation for information

00:14:27.203 --> 00:14:27.923
visualization.

00:14:28.524 --> 00:14:34.323
Um, and instead it's better to pick kind of a bog standard, um, you know, the DOM

00:14:34.323 --> 00:14:39.083
API, SVG, something that's not specialized to visualization and just use that even

00:14:39.083 --> 00:14:44.284
though it's not kind of designed with visualization in mind, but you get so many

00:14:44.303 --> 00:14:50.184
advantages from interoperating with browser technology, like being able to use your

00:14:50.184 --> 00:14:54.383
style sheets or being able to use the browser's dev tools, or being able to kind

00:14:54.383 --> 00:14:58.224
of integrate with, uh, React or other like DOM APIs.

00:14:58.784 --> 00:15:03.983
And so I think the, you know, from the research community, I think those kind of

00:15:03.983 --> 00:15:06.823
practical benefits of the technology weren't as obvious.

00:15:07.143 --> 00:15:10.904
And so it was somewhat, uh, heretical to come in there and saying like, let's not try

00:15:10.923 --> 00:15:15.284
to build a specialized representation, but just take this thing that exists already and

00:15:15.284 --> 00:15:19.844
focus on kind of the more practical benefits of like how it gets put into practice.

00:15:19.844 --> 00:15:21.844
Cause people never use these tools in isolation.

00:15:21.844 --> 00:15:23.803
They're always using them with all sorts of other things.

00:15:24.363 --> 00:15:28.124
I mean, it's like, it's hard to remember now, but this is also like, like this

00:15:28.124 --> 00:15:30.124
JavaScript was kind of like a joke language.

00:15:30.124 --> 00:15:34.043
Like this is still, it was still a joke language at the time, like it was slow.

00:15:34.043 --> 00:15:35.164
You're saying compared to R.

00:15:36.883 --> 00:15:40.323
But just like, it wasn't like people didn't consider it a real programming language

00:15:40.344 --> 00:15:45.303
and like how all these performance issues, but like you clearly could have sort of saw

00:15:45.303 --> 00:15:48.543
like, Hey, the browser is going to be really important for visualization.

00:15:48.543 --> 00:15:49.543
Like let's, that's right.

00:15:49.543 --> 00:15:49.744
Yeah.

00:15:49.744 --> 00:15:50.583
It on that.

00:15:50.643 --> 00:15:54.423
And I obviously like JavaScript has made tremendous strides in terms of its

00:15:54.423 --> 00:15:55.944
performance and its capabilities.

00:15:55.944 --> 00:16:00.064
And it's kind of nothing like it was, you know, 20 years ago, but I think from my

00:16:00.064 --> 00:16:04.203
side, like it was always inevitable that that would happen because, you know, it

00:16:04.203 --> 00:16:10.344
really is the, the interface that all human beings are like interacting with their

00:16:10.344 --> 00:16:12.303
computers, with their displays of data.

00:16:12.784 --> 00:16:16.784
Like it's really hard to compete with the convenience of delivery through

00:16:16.784 --> 00:16:18.383
the web, like through browsers.

00:16:19.143 --> 00:16:19.444
Yeah.

00:16:19.444 --> 00:16:22.784
Like, I think an interesting, like, I was just kind of thinking, like, imagine a

00:16:22.784 --> 00:16:28.583
world where you were like, I love Java applets, I'm going to like invest in that.

00:16:28.983 --> 00:16:32.103
But in some ways that that's a little bit like processing, which was kind of

00:16:32.244 --> 00:16:38.724
around a similar time, like the, not, not for visual, like more of like art, like a

00:16:38.724 --> 00:16:43.444
system for programming art that was really all in on like Java applets, I think that

00:16:43.444 --> 00:16:47.763
was, and, you know, and I think that's still thrive is still thriving today, but

00:16:47.763 --> 00:16:52.244
if had to like make a lot of like technological leaps to kind of stay for

00:16:52.244 --> 00:16:57.603
like D3, I think there is something inherently beautiful about kind of HTML

00:16:57.703 --> 00:17:03.423
and the DOM, this idea that it is not kind of an opaque representation of a

00:17:03.423 --> 00:17:07.504
graphical user interface, but in fact is something that you can inspect and then

00:17:07.504 --> 00:17:08.504
even manipulate.

00:17:08.863 --> 00:17:11.983
So there's all sorts of benefits to the user from that.

00:17:11.983 --> 00:17:16.464
I mean, like ad blockers is probably the most obvious one, but like screen readers

00:17:16.464 --> 00:17:18.383
or other accessibility improvements.

00:17:18.383 --> 00:17:22.744
And like, it just, it is dramatically different than an application that, for

00:17:22.744 --> 00:17:27.603
example, just draws to like a pixel buffer or whatever, that just is a array of RGP

00:17:27.603 --> 00:17:28.763
values effectively.

00:17:29.363 --> 00:17:32.203
And I think that is key to its success.

00:17:32.724 --> 00:17:36.203
And do you think it helps that like, you can go in and like inspect, like you can go

00:17:36.203 --> 00:17:40.203
into a D3, like inspect this DOM and be like, oh, okay, there's now I understand

00:17:40.203 --> 00:17:41.203
like what's going on.

00:17:41.844 --> 00:17:46.363
And, you know, that's how I got into programming in the first place, like growing

00:17:46.363 --> 00:17:48.004
up and like seeing web pages.

00:17:48.004 --> 00:17:49.564
I mean, you can't really do it these days.

00:17:50.423 --> 00:17:53.143
Cause there's like 35 megabytes, minified.

00:17:53.143 --> 00:17:53.504
Yeah.

00:17:53.983 --> 00:17:57.863
But in the old days, you know, you could go to a website and you could just like click on

00:17:57.863 --> 00:18:00.543
the menu and view source and they'd be like, how did you do this?

00:18:00.543 --> 00:18:00.784
You know?

00:18:00.784 --> 00:18:02.744
And it would be right there, kind of obvious.

00:18:03.024 --> 00:18:03.823
You could inspect it.

00:18:03.823 --> 00:18:04.744
You could learn from it.

00:18:05.383 --> 00:18:09.543
And so there are some challenges now with the complexity of modern development, but

00:18:09.543 --> 00:18:14.944
even so like, yeah, the ability to kind of inspect the SVG and kind of see how it's

00:18:14.944 --> 00:18:17.863
structured, like definitely gives you some, some clues.

00:18:18.524 --> 00:18:23.043
And then with D3 in particular, I've enjoyed sometimes like it, you bind the data to the

00:18:23.043 --> 00:18:23.564
elements.

00:18:23.564 --> 00:18:27.244
So using the dev tools, you can actually see the data structures that people are using

00:18:27.244 --> 00:18:27.923
in their charts.

00:18:28.603 --> 00:18:31.164
And that's kind of fun to understand how they work also.

00:18:31.524 --> 00:18:32.043
Yeah.

00:18:32.643 --> 00:18:38.124
I, one thing I'm curious to, to hit on is, the popularity of D3.

00:18:38.124 --> 00:18:44.763
As I looked back, someone mentioned, I think, D3 was like one of the top starred

00:18:44.763 --> 00:18:46.123
GitHub repos.

00:18:46.164 --> 00:18:46.563
Yeah.

00:18:46.724 --> 00:18:47.123
Is that?

00:18:47.224 --> 00:18:49.104
It was number three at one point.

00:18:49.104 --> 00:18:49.383
Okay.

00:18:49.503 --> 00:18:53.183
After like Bootstrap and React, I think was the other one.

00:18:53.224 --> 00:18:53.383
Yeah.

00:18:53.383 --> 00:18:55.743
But yeah, it was very popular.

00:18:56.263 --> 00:19:01.143
And I think at one point I've heard that just a tremendous amount of traffic was going

00:19:01.143 --> 00:19:02.503
to the D3 wiki.

00:19:02.984 --> 00:19:06.503
So I think one of, one of the things that made, I think that helped D3 grow as a

00:19:06.503 --> 00:19:11.344
community was the fact that the, all the documentation was just an editable, publicly

00:19:11.344 --> 00:19:12.864
editable wiki on GitHub.

00:19:13.323 --> 00:19:18.443
So anybody could go in there and like people contributed translations to all

00:19:18.443 --> 00:19:22.284
different languages, as well as kind of like fixing typos and stuff like that.

00:19:22.643 --> 00:19:26.844
But I think the thing that had the most kind of momentum around it was the gallery.

00:19:27.203 --> 00:19:31.804
So it started with just some thumbnails of examples that I had made, often ones that

00:19:31.804 --> 00:19:35.683
imported from Protoviz, but there was this kind of rite of passage in the D3

00:19:35.683 --> 00:19:39.203
community where people would learn D3 and maybe the first or second or whatever

00:19:39.203 --> 00:19:42.604
visualization that they made, they would take a screenshot of it and they would add

00:19:42.623 --> 00:19:43.464
it to the gallery.

00:19:44.063 --> 00:19:47.544
And so very quickly there were like a thousand examples that various people had

00:19:47.544 --> 00:19:52.024
contributed and you just went there and it was this overwhelming display of kind of all

00:19:52.024 --> 00:19:54.063
the different cool things that people were building.

00:19:54.424 --> 00:19:56.464
A lot of them were like animated GIFs as well.

00:19:56.503 --> 00:19:57.904
So you would see things moving around.

00:19:58.443 --> 00:20:02.823
Unfortunately, then once it became popular, you know, spammers started putting links in

00:20:02.823 --> 00:20:06.063
their like malware and stuff and it just became unmanageable.

00:20:06.104 --> 00:20:07.383
So I had to take that down.

00:20:08.003 --> 00:20:08.284
Yeah.

00:20:08.804 --> 00:20:13.484
Was that a precursor because I know you had blocks, is that right?

00:20:13.524 --> 00:20:13.844
Yeah.

00:20:14.555 --> 00:20:16.955
Could you explain a little bit about what blocks?

00:20:16.955 --> 00:20:20.955
Okay, so I was making all these examples to help people learn D3.

00:20:20.955 --> 00:20:25.915
And very often, when people would ask questions, so we had the Google Groups mailing list.

00:20:26.077 --> 00:20:29.677
which is the primary way that people would ask questions. I think now it's more on GitHub

00:20:29.677 --> 00:20:33.277
discussions and that sort of thing. But people would ask a question, I'd be like, okay, I'm

00:20:33.277 --> 00:20:37.597
going to make an example for you that shows you how to do this. And it just kind of became

00:20:38.237 --> 00:20:43.517
difficult to manage all of those examples. And so I started to build some machinery around making it

00:20:43.517 --> 00:20:48.796
easier for me to manage those examples. Because I didn't want to kind of keep uploading them to

00:20:48.796 --> 00:20:53.677
a website. And even just naming, like the folder name started to become difficult to come up with

00:20:53.677 --> 00:20:59.036
a good name for these things when you have like a thousand examples. So I started using GitHub Gist,

00:20:59.036 --> 00:21:04.957
which is just like a very lightweight Git repo that has just a randomly generated giant hex

00:21:04.957 --> 00:21:12.237
string as its name. And you could put an index.html file in there. But what I needed was just a way to

00:21:12.237 --> 00:21:20.557
like actually render that HTML page. And so blocks, which is bl.ocks.org, is just a viewer for GitHub

00:21:20.557 --> 00:21:25.437
Gists. And so you could then have a URL, you give it a Gist ID, and people could go look at that

00:21:25.437 --> 00:21:29.437
example, and it would show you the source code below. And so that kind of became the primary

00:21:29.437 --> 00:21:33.517
way that I started sharing examples. And of course, since it was on GitHub Gist, anybody else could

00:21:33.517 --> 00:21:39.276
start sharing their examples as well. Do I remember it was like bl.ocks, and then it was like also

00:21:40.077 --> 00:21:46.716
bostock? Yeah, so bostock. So I bought the ocks.org domain name just because it was nice and

00:21:46.716 --> 00:21:51.276
short. And then I can put whatever other domains on it or hosts on it.

00:21:52.157 --> 00:21:56.557
Yeah, it's such an interesting one. I know you talked about in your 10 years of open source,

00:21:57.197 --> 00:22:02.316
I'm curious your thoughts on how do you approach documentation?

00:22:02.956 --> 00:22:08.797
Well, that feedback loop is, I think, the most exciting, most valuable, most powerful thing about

00:22:08.797 --> 00:22:13.356
open source, where you're putting something out there, and then you get to see how people use it.

00:22:13.356 --> 00:22:16.877
And they're asking you, like, how do I do this? Or how do I do that? Or they're complaining about

00:22:16.877 --> 00:22:23.596
something or whatever, or they're giving you ideas. And being in that feedback loop, getting

00:22:23.596 --> 00:22:28.477
all of those new ideas is what really helps you advance the tool, make the tool better,

00:22:28.477 --> 00:22:33.036
because you understand the problems that people are running into, and the ideas that they have

00:22:33.036 --> 00:22:39.437
of other stuff that you can add, and that other people can then benefit from once you've incorporated

00:22:39.437 --> 00:22:46.397
it into the tool. And so documentation is part of that. But I think examples has been another huge

00:22:46.397 --> 00:22:52.957
part of that. And in many ways, I think people view the D3 examples as kind of more of what D3 is

00:22:52.957 --> 00:22:58.556
than D3 itself, if that makes sense. I think there was something that I read once that talked about

00:22:58.556 --> 00:23:02.476
all the different chart types that were supported in D3. And I was like, no, you've got it all wrong.

00:23:02.476 --> 00:23:07.196
Like there aren't chart types in D3. But what they're thinking of is the examples that you

00:23:07.196 --> 00:23:13.276
provide. And they can just be copied and adapted with new data that's being put into it or whatever.

00:23:14.237 --> 00:23:20.317
And so I think the examples, as I've written before, they serve multiple purposes. And

00:23:20.317 --> 00:23:25.276
sometimes it's kind of giving you example code, like helping you get started with something,

00:23:25.276 --> 00:23:30.877
showing you how to use something. Sometimes it's inspirational, where you're just showing what's

00:23:30.877 --> 00:23:37.276
possible, kind of the breadth of possibilities in a particular tool, and kind of getting people

00:23:37.276 --> 00:23:42.797
excited about what they could be doing with it. Yeah, you give a talk about examples. Yeah,

00:23:42.797 --> 00:23:47.356
I found that like really, that was like really influential for me and like guided a lot. I think

00:23:47.356 --> 00:23:52.476
a lot of the R package docs. Yeah, like people, people don't really want to read the docs,

00:23:52.476 --> 00:23:56.957
right? They just want to scroll, find something that looks like what they want and like modify.

00:23:56.957 --> 00:24:00.157
Yeah. I mean, especially if you're making a visualization tool, you know, you have to show

00:24:00.157 --> 00:24:04.716
people the visualizations to get them excited about its capabilities. So that's always been

00:24:04.716 --> 00:24:12.636
front and center in what I've done. I think the interesting now with AI is whether that demand,

00:24:12.636 --> 00:24:17.517
for examples, will still be there in a sense, or like whether people will ask the agents essentially

00:24:17.517 --> 00:24:23.116
to construct the example that they want at the time that they want it. So one of the things that

00:24:23.116 --> 00:24:27.037
people struggle with, with the examples, like if there's an example, that's exactly what you want,

00:24:27.037 --> 00:24:31.996
then great. But, you know, the whole idea of D3 is that it can be really expressive and do

00:24:31.996 --> 00:24:37.276
all sorts of things. So you typically don't want just that example and use it off the shelf. Like

00:24:37.276 --> 00:24:41.597
maybe you like this example, and then there's another technique from another example and

00:24:41.597 --> 00:24:45.756
another and so on. And you kind of want to stitch them together to build the thing that's unique to

00:24:45.756 --> 00:24:50.797
you. It can be hard to do that, particularly if you're new to D3 or if you're new to programming,

00:24:50.797 --> 00:24:57.117
but models agents are really good at kind of fitting those two things together. So it's good

00:24:57.117 --> 00:25:01.837
in empowering people, but it also, I think, is a little bit worrisome from the open source

00:25:01.837 --> 00:25:06.557
community perspective where there's not as much of an incentive for users to come read the

00:25:06.557 --> 00:25:12.316
documentation, to come look at the examples or to share their own examples or to ask for help,

00:25:12.316 --> 00:25:17.036
because they can just kind of ask an agent for those things. Do you feel like your strategy

00:25:17.036 --> 00:25:23.277
for documentation has changed with the age of AI? No, because I'm stubborn maybe or slow.

00:25:24.557 --> 00:25:29.117
I mean, I know that there are people that are doing like llms.txt or whatever and like trying

00:25:29.117 --> 00:25:36.077
to make it even more easily consumable by AI. But I think, you know, my attitude is I don't really

00:25:36.077 --> 00:25:41.196
want to write documentation specifically for agents or for existing models. I mean, for one

00:25:41.196 --> 00:25:46.557
reason, like they're going to change all the time. And so if you overfit to whatever the current

00:25:46.636 --> 00:25:52.077
models are, when the next model comes out, like it may not work as well. And so in that sense,

00:25:52.077 --> 00:25:58.077
I would want to build something more durable. And so if it works for the models, then great.

00:25:58.876 --> 00:26:04.397
But I also want it to be understandable by humans and trying to teach humans. And it can be a really

00:26:04.397 --> 00:26:09.517
good forcing function to figure out or at least another kind of feedback mechanism to figure out

00:26:09.517 --> 00:26:15.277
like how to explain something to somebody. Like how do I articulate when you should use a certain

00:26:15.277 --> 00:26:21.677
argument or option and plot or not? You know, you can very quickly evaluate that with the agent,

00:26:21.677 --> 00:26:25.997
whereas like actually doing that with humans is much more expensive or slower because you have

00:26:25.997 --> 00:26:29.517
to put it out there and see what they do or do user research and stuff like that.

00:26:29.517 --> 00:26:34.876
Yeah, makes sense. I'm curious what your setup is like when you're working. You mentioned like

00:26:34.876 --> 00:26:39.356
working with agents and their use of examples. What does your setup look like when you're

00:26:39.356 --> 00:26:44.957
developing? Sure. I mean, a lot of it is unobservable for sharing these examples these

00:26:44.957 --> 00:26:51.756
days. So, you know, when I'm publishing D3 examples, I'm doing it as an observable notebook

00:26:51.756 --> 00:27:00.636
and we're sharing it on the D3 whatever page on observable. For like application development,

00:27:00.636 --> 00:27:07.117
like when we're building observable, I use Z as my primary editor and it does have like an agent

00:27:07.117 --> 00:27:12.316
built in there. But I think, you know, I don't maybe I feel embarrassed like admitting this in

00:27:12.316 --> 00:27:17.117
the public, but like I don't, you know, I don't use cloud code to do a lot of like vibe coding

00:27:17.117 --> 00:27:24.876
stuff right now. I think I do use agents often kind of as a substitute for searching the web

00:27:24.876 --> 00:27:29.436
or looking up documentation. I mean, there's so many tools that we're using right now.

00:27:29.436 --> 00:27:33.997
It's impossible for you to kind of have the API reference memorized for every tool that you're

00:27:33.997 --> 00:27:39.196
using. And so in the past, you know, I would search the web for, you know, how do I do this?

00:27:39.196 --> 00:27:43.436
Maybe it's Stack Overflow, maybe it's the official documentation, that sort of thing.

00:27:43.997 --> 00:27:50.237
But with agents, you know, they can often surface example code that helps you understand how to use

00:27:50.237 --> 00:27:54.717
an API. And so it's not kind of writing the whole thing for you, but it is filling in

00:27:54.717 --> 00:27:59.196
gaps in your knowledge and then you can test it and see if it's doing what you want to do.

00:27:59.196 --> 00:28:05.277
Yeah, I found it so useful for like for dbply, which translates dply syntax into SQL, like,

00:28:05.277 --> 00:28:10.957
oh, I want to know what this syntax looks like across 10 different database backends.

00:28:11.677 --> 00:28:15.997
And like previously, I would have been doing a bunch of like Googling, like trying to

00:28:15.997 --> 00:28:20.237
we weighed my way through the official docs. And like, you get the answer in the end,

00:28:20.237 --> 00:28:24.156
but like Claude just does it all in parallel. And then it just makes me a nice little table.

00:28:24.156 --> 00:28:30.077
And like, even if it's only like 90% correct, like it's still saved me so much time.

00:28:30.077 --> 00:28:33.436
And it can often surface APIs that you didn't even know existed,

00:28:33.596 --> 00:28:35.277
you wouldn't know to go look for it.

00:28:35.277 --> 00:28:37.997
Yeah, I'm curious, you mentioned working in the observable notebook,

00:28:37.997 --> 00:28:43.036
this might be a good chance for us to explain what observable notebooks are a little bit.

00:28:44.717 --> 00:28:51.117
Even with, I'm even curious, this sort of move from like D3, working on D3 to founding

00:28:51.837 --> 00:28:53.997
observable, what that looked like.

00:28:53.997 --> 00:28:58.477
So, you know, my interest in building tools in general is like, how do you take these

00:28:59.037 --> 00:29:04.077
valuable skills, expertise, practices, and make them more broadly accessible.

00:29:04.717 --> 00:29:09.436
And a big part of that for me has been programming, like most of the tools that I build are

00:29:09.436 --> 00:29:15.917
programming tools, programming libraries. I love the power of code, the generality of code,

00:29:15.917 --> 00:29:21.037
kind of these compositional primitives that you can deploy in all sorts of interesting

00:29:21.037 --> 00:29:25.917
and creative ways. It's not like there are six chart types with whatever 10 options each

00:29:25.917 --> 00:29:30.636
or something like that. You can really have a lot of flexibility in what you create and

00:29:30.636 --> 00:29:35.917
not just visualization too. I mean, again, visualization is not just kind of a thing

00:29:35.917 --> 00:29:42.636
that you do in isolation. It's like, what data are you using? And how are you kind of

00:29:42.636 --> 00:29:46.717
modeling or transforming that data into kind of an interesting representation that you

00:29:46.717 --> 00:29:51.037
can then visualize? And then how are you sharing that visualization or distributing it?

00:29:51.917 --> 00:29:57.357
There's all sorts of other tasks that go alongside visualization. So I love the power of

00:29:57.357 --> 00:30:03.116
code, but of course, it is difficult to use. Let's be honest, there's a lot of things that

00:30:03.116 --> 00:30:09.196
you need to learn. And so I've always been interested in how can I make code more accessible

00:30:09.196 --> 00:30:13.996
and then how can I make visualization more accessible? So, you know, we were talking

00:30:13.996 --> 00:30:19.756
about blocks.org earlier as a way for people or as a way for me to share examples and then

00:30:19.756 --> 00:30:23.597
other people would share examples as well. But, you know, one of the issues of that is

00:30:23.597 --> 00:30:29.357
still very much a local development environment, right? You typically would git clone a GitHub

00:30:29.357 --> 00:30:33.996
gist. You'd have a web server running locally. You would use your code editor. You know,

00:30:33.996 --> 00:30:37.597
those are some barriers to entry in order to just get started.

00:30:37.709 --> 00:30:41.669
And so, what I wanted was something that was web-based, where you wouldn't have to install

00:30:41.669 --> 00:30:42.669
anything.

00:30:42.669 --> 00:30:46.069
You would just go to the webpage, and not only would you see the example, but you could

00:30:46.069 --> 00:30:47.069
edit it.

00:30:47.069 --> 00:30:51.909
You know, you could change the code, you could replace the data, you could do kind of any

00:30:51.909 --> 00:30:57.989
number of things, because it's an entire development environment that runs in your browser.

00:30:57.989 --> 00:31:01.529
And furthermore, like a social, collaborative development environment, where you could share

00:31:01.529 --> 00:31:06.069
what you've built, you could import code from other examples, and stuff like that.

00:31:06.549 --> 00:31:11.709
And that comes from the open-source mindset, where working out in the public lets people

00:31:11.709 --> 00:31:16.709
kind of inspire each other, and share techniques, and in general, kind of advances the state

00:31:16.709 --> 00:31:21.749
of the art much faster than anything that doesn't have that same level of collaboration.

00:31:21.749 --> 00:31:27.828
So Observable started as this way of like, how can I make programming more accessible?

00:31:27.828 --> 00:31:31.109
Like moving it to the web, so you don't need any development environment.

00:31:31.148 --> 00:31:36.789
But it was also, in a way, like rethinking some of the aspects of programming.

00:31:36.789 --> 00:31:42.149
So yes, it's a computational notebook, you know, like Jupyter, you have cells, you can

00:31:42.149 --> 00:31:45.829
run cells, and they can display things, and they can compute values.

00:31:45.829 --> 00:31:49.389
But I think one of the key differences, one of the key innovations of the Observable notebook

00:31:49.389 --> 00:31:51.268
was reactivity.

00:31:51.268 --> 00:31:56.069
This idea, like in a spreadsheet, where you don't have to manually run the cells, that

00:31:56.069 --> 00:31:59.988
instead, it understands the topological relationships.

00:31:59.988 --> 00:32:05.389
So if you declare a variable in one cell, and then you reference it in another cell,

00:32:05.389 --> 00:32:09.668
when you redefine that variable, any referencing cell runs automatically.

00:32:09.668 --> 00:32:14.429
And it's just like kind of a bookkeeping thing, in a sense, where like, you as the author

00:32:14.429 --> 00:32:19.128
of your program, don't have to remember to keep rerunning things, or worry about being

00:32:19.128 --> 00:32:23.189
in this kind of inconsistent state where you've changed the code, but you've forgotten to

00:32:23.189 --> 00:32:27.808
rerun certain downstream cells, and so like, it's not matching up what you expect.

00:32:27.808 --> 00:32:32.649
So like, spreadsheet programming, I think, has made that form of programming much more

00:32:32.649 --> 00:32:33.889
accessible.

00:32:33.889 --> 00:32:37.168
But you only have these tiny little cells that can produce numbers, and in a sense,

00:32:37.168 --> 00:32:42.609
I just wanted bigger cells that could produce graphical outputs as well.

00:32:42.609 --> 00:32:46.949
And the other thing that comes along with this reactivity model is basically anything

00:32:46.949 --> 00:32:51.248
can become user controlled, anything that can become interactive.

00:32:51.248 --> 00:32:55.888
And so you can take, you know, a number, like, let's say you're building an inflation calculator

00:32:55.888 --> 00:33:00.848
or something, and you want to, like, have a given a certain amount in a certain year,

00:33:00.848 --> 00:33:04.729
and you want to say, like, what is that value in today's dollars, rather than having to

00:33:04.729 --> 00:33:09.089
edit the code to change what the number is, like, just replace that with a slider.

00:33:09.089 --> 00:33:13.169
And because it's reactive, you don't have to change anything downstream, like any constant

00:33:13.169 --> 00:33:16.488
variable can be turned into something that's interactive, or turned into something that's

00:33:16.488 --> 00:33:18.968
animated and stuff like that.

00:33:18.968 --> 00:33:24.809
And my because my experience from D3 was a lot of that kind of interactivity, like the

00:33:24.809 --> 00:33:29.128
asynchronous nature of loading data, and kind of handling all of these different states,

00:33:29.128 --> 00:33:34.128
like that was the hardest part, in a way, about making interactive visualizations.

00:33:34.128 --> 00:33:39.369
And so if you could handle that at the language layer, or by with the runtime, then it's kind

00:33:39.369 --> 00:33:40.809
of a simpler way of thinking about it.

00:33:40.809 --> 00:33:44.809
Are you saying you're saying a lot of the problem was even just getting data in, yeah,

00:33:44.809 --> 00:33:48.048
maybe doing some stuff with it before, yeah, hit the plot.

00:33:48.048 --> 00:33:53.688
I mean, so just as a small example, like on the blocks, examples, you would, it's like

00:33:53.688 --> 00:33:56.809
pre promises, so you would use these callback functions.

00:33:56.809 --> 00:34:02.848
So you do like d3.json, or d3.csv, or something, and then there'd be a callback function.

00:34:02.848 --> 00:34:06.408
And there was always this question of like, what goes in the callback function versus

00:34:06.408 --> 00:34:08.768
like what goes outside the callback function?

00:34:08.768 --> 00:34:12.248
What do you do if you want to load multiple data sets and join them together?

00:34:12.248 --> 00:34:14.888
Like do you nest them together, which is slow?

00:34:14.888 --> 00:34:19.569
Do you use another, I've read another library that's called d3q, which is like for running,

00:34:19.569 --> 00:34:24.128
it's totally obsolete now with promises, you just say promise.all.

00:34:24.128 --> 00:34:29.809
But there are all these kind of mechanical concerns about asynchronous state or handling

00:34:29.809 --> 00:34:36.089
interaction that I think, you know, is just another barrier for people to produce a good

00:34:36.089 --> 00:34:37.089
visualization.

00:34:37.089 --> 00:34:41.328
So I wanted to think about that problem, and make it easier for people to express these

00:34:41.328 --> 00:34:43.209
reactive or interactive programs.

00:34:43.248 --> 00:34:48.369
I'm really curious, there's the new idea of like the observable whiteboards, and how does

00:34:48.369 --> 00:34:49.369
that fit in?

00:34:49.369 --> 00:34:51.209
Like, is this a next generation notebook?

00:34:51.209 --> 00:34:53.328
Is this replacing dashboards?

00:34:53.328 --> 00:34:58.448
Where do these whiteboards, which are like, almost sticky notes as a Jupyter notebooky

00:34:58.448 --> 00:34:59.448
thing?

00:34:59.448 --> 00:35:00.448
Yeah.

00:35:00.448 --> 00:35:01.448
Where does this fit in?

00:35:01.448 --> 00:35:08.129
So I think, you know, we have observable canvases, which has kind of been an alternative to notebooks.

00:35:08.129 --> 00:35:11.969
And the idea is like, you know, what happens if instead of essentially like a linear layout

00:35:11.969 --> 00:35:17.568
in a document, you have a infinite canvas, like a 2d layout?

00:35:17.568 --> 00:35:23.129
I think it's been an interesting experiment for us to think about, like, how we can build

00:35:23.129 --> 00:35:26.768
more UI versus building more code.

00:35:26.768 --> 00:35:31.328
Like there are, like, there's the substrate difference, I guess, between a canvas and

00:35:31.328 --> 00:35:32.328
a notebook.

00:35:32.328 --> 00:35:34.849
But there's also like the different components and stuff like that.

00:35:34.849 --> 00:35:39.448
I think after, you know, we've spent about a year on canvases, I think we are basically

00:35:39.448 --> 00:35:42.608
heading back to notebooks at this point.

00:35:42.608 --> 00:35:46.649
Having learned some of the innovation that we're able to get through canvases.

00:35:46.649 --> 00:35:51.608
I think canvases was also an opportunity for us to revisit how the AI works.

00:35:51.608 --> 00:35:58.168
And having AI being more integrated into kind of your data exploration and your visualization.

00:35:58.168 --> 00:36:01.969
And so we have some exciting stuff that we've been working on that pulls that back into

00:36:01.969 --> 00:36:03.969
notebooks as well.

00:36:03.969 --> 00:36:12.168
But the challenge has been, like, having kind of fractured or disparate tools.

00:36:12.168 --> 00:36:18.388
And so one of our lessons is, like, we want to build on, like, notebooks as the foundation.

00:36:18.388 --> 00:36:23.168
So that you can easily move between kind of different ways of working without kind of

00:36:23.168 --> 00:36:28.568
having disparate applications that don't work well with each other.

00:36:28.568 --> 00:36:31.328
It sounds like you learned a lot doing canvas.

00:36:31.888 --> 00:36:36.888
It sounds like through canvas, you learned a lot about what notebooks can give people,

00:36:36.888 --> 00:36:37.888
maybe?

00:36:37.888 --> 00:36:38.888
Is that?

00:36:38.888 --> 00:36:39.888
Yeah.

00:36:39.888 --> 00:36:42.488
I mean, I think we're always learning in terms of what's working and what's not working and

00:36:42.488 --> 00:36:47.689
trying to kind of push that envelope in terms of how do I make this more accessible?

00:36:47.689 --> 00:36:54.089
So I think with the reactivity, with the web-based development, I think absolutely we've made

00:36:54.089 --> 00:36:59.328
progress in terms of making kind of interactive visualization more accessible or making web

00:36:59.328 --> 00:37:03.168
development, let's call it, more accessible as well.

00:37:03.168 --> 00:37:07.168
But I think, you know, there still clearly is a barrier to entry there.

00:37:07.168 --> 00:37:12.728
And one of the questions is, like, can you solve that through UI or can you solve it

00:37:12.728 --> 00:37:14.929
through AI?

00:37:14.929 --> 00:37:19.809
And I think a year ago, I mean, these things are changing so quickly, but I think over

00:37:19.809 --> 00:37:23.888
the last few years, I think we've been doing a lot of work on the UI.

00:37:23.888 --> 00:37:28.048
And I think we've made progress, but it is very challenging to do.

00:37:28.929 --> 00:37:33.048
No matter what the UI looks like, it feels like you're sacrificing a lot of the expressiveness

00:37:33.048 --> 00:37:34.048
of it.

00:37:34.048 --> 00:37:36.168
And it's very expensive to build UI.

00:37:36.168 --> 00:37:40.969
And so even if we build a great UI for visualization, what happens if you don't know where your

00:37:40.969 --> 00:37:41.969
data is, right?

00:37:41.969 --> 00:37:45.969
Or you want to cross-reference data from different sources?

00:37:45.969 --> 00:37:51.328
Often there are public datasets that you want to pull in to correlate with whatever proprietary

00:37:51.328 --> 00:37:53.488
data that you're using.

00:37:53.488 --> 00:37:55.488
And that's a whole nother technical challenge.

00:37:55.488 --> 00:37:59.409
If you want to do self-serve analytics or whatever, you want to kind of bring in a broader

00:37:59.409 --> 00:38:01.649
audience to be able to use these tools.

00:38:01.649 --> 00:38:03.809
You can't just do the visualization part of it.

00:38:03.809 --> 00:38:07.288
Like, it's all of the other parts that you have to support.

00:38:07.288 --> 00:38:11.768
And so I think we've made progress in the UI, but it's just, it's been very expensive

00:38:11.768 --> 00:38:16.728
to kind of build out enough to really make a difference in terms of the accessibility

00:38:16.728 --> 00:38:18.228
of it.

00:38:18.228 --> 00:38:22.189
And I think now with the advancement in AI, it feels like there's a whole new opportunity

00:38:22.268 --> 00:38:25.469
to kind of go back to a code-based approach.

00:38:25.469 --> 00:38:31.189
And so in a way, like we're very well situated in that these computational notebooks and

00:38:31.189 --> 00:38:37.268
the Reactivity in particular are, you know, more human accessible form of programming,

00:38:37.268 --> 00:38:41.709
but it turns out they work exceptionally well for the agents as well, because you can take

00:38:41.709 --> 00:38:46.828
really complex programming problems and break them down into smaller steps, kind of run

00:38:46.828 --> 00:38:50.749
the code incrementally, see what happens, inspect the results, and kind of iterate and

00:38:50.749 --> 00:38:52.168
learn from that.

00:38:52.168 --> 00:38:56.249
And ultimately the goal is that that code, even if it is produced by an agent, should

00:38:56.249 --> 00:38:59.568
be understandable, interpretable by a human.

00:38:59.568 --> 00:39:03.349
Like we don't want to create these black box solutions where we don't understand what it's

00:39:03.349 --> 00:39:06.469
doing and therefore can't trust the output of it.

00:39:06.469 --> 00:39:12.808
So I think it's nice to have this more accessible medium, even if it has the AI in there to

00:39:12.808 --> 00:39:18.849
kind of let people write code without, you know, spending years becoming a professional

00:39:18.849 --> 00:39:19.849
programmer.

00:39:20.368 --> 00:39:22.128
It's so interesting, the notebook.

00:39:22.128 --> 00:39:28.008
I feel like I've also, I've really come around to notebooks in the past year as a tool versus

00:39:28.008 --> 00:39:34.489
like before I was doing a lot of text-based, these like R Markdown, QMD, it's like a text

00:39:34.489 --> 00:39:36.489
document that renders.

00:39:36.489 --> 00:39:40.729
But I do feel like the use of agents in notebooks has really, I've been thinking about it a

00:39:40.729 --> 00:39:45.649
lot recently, and I do feel like Observable, with a lot of these experiments, and also

00:39:45.649 --> 00:39:51.489
Observable was way ahead of the curve on this like graph, this reactive execution of

00:39:51.489 --> 00:39:53.448
cells and things.

00:39:53.448 --> 00:39:54.568
I'm curious your thoughts.

00:39:54.568 --> 00:40:00.969
I know notebooks have had an interesting history with, I think, people like Joel Grews, who

00:40:00.969 --> 00:40:03.849
famously came out against the notebook, and Jeremy Howard, who...

00:40:03.849 --> 00:40:08.089
Well, I think specifically about the kind of the lack of reactivity in Jupyter and this

00:40:08.089 --> 00:40:11.049
problem of like inconsistent state and stuff like that.

00:40:11.049 --> 00:40:12.049
Yeah, yeah.

00:40:12.049 --> 00:40:13.049
Okay.

00:40:13.049 --> 00:40:14.049
So that's like the kind of the key.

00:40:14.049 --> 00:40:22.289
I'm curious your thoughts on like the evolution of notebooks and what do notebooks do that's

00:40:22.289 --> 00:40:23.289
like so useful?

00:40:23.289 --> 00:40:24.289
Yeah.

00:40:24.289 --> 00:40:28.969
Well, we've always been an interesting outlier, I think, not just from the reactivity side,

00:40:28.969 --> 00:40:33.169
but also from the JavaScript side, where like we're really focused on kind of the front

00:40:33.169 --> 00:40:40.448
end, the interface, the kind of live computation, interactive documents, interactive applications,

00:40:40.448 --> 00:40:41.448
interactive visualization.

00:40:41.448 --> 00:40:42.448
Yeah.

00:40:42.448 --> 00:40:43.448
Yeah.

00:40:41.454 --> 00:40:47.614
I don't know if I can speak to whatever the lessons have been from Jupiter because we've

00:40:47.614 --> 00:40:52.214
been this kind of anomaly, in a sense.

00:40:52.584 --> 00:40:59.224
You know, again, we have, I think, made progress in terms of making programming more accessible.

00:40:59.224 --> 00:41:03.984
And I do think notebooks are a significant — they're a different thing than building

00:41:03.984 --> 00:41:04.984
an application.

00:41:04.984 --> 00:41:09.664
You know, like, they're not really a replacement for building a whole web app or building a

00:41:09.664 --> 00:41:14.944
desktop application, but at the same time, like, there needs to be something that kind

00:41:14.944 --> 00:41:20.864
of sits between, let's say, a full software application and, like, a Google Doc or a Word

00:41:20.864 --> 00:41:23.664
Doc or something that's completely static.

00:41:23.664 --> 00:41:29.464
And you know, it's great to have a live dataset or a live visualization or even, like, an

00:41:29.464 --> 00:41:35.744
interactive model that can be embedded directly within that document so that you can kind

00:41:35.744 --> 00:41:39.144
of tinker with the parameters and kind of see what happens.

00:41:39.144 --> 00:41:43.383
And it's still — as I said, I think prior — my hope is that the coding agents are

00:41:43.383 --> 00:41:47.703
really going to help make this more accessible to the broader audience.

00:41:47.703 --> 00:41:52.784
But for the people over the last 10 years or however long that have had that skill,

00:41:52.784 --> 00:41:58.484
have been able to do programming, I think notebooks are a really exciting medium for

00:41:58.484 --> 00:42:03.143
explaining things and kind of making things feel more hands-on.

00:42:03.143 --> 00:42:07.304
You know, like Brett Victor has talked about, like, being an active reader.

00:42:07.304 --> 00:42:12.103
So you're not just kind of reading whatever the words are or whatever the numbers are

00:42:12.103 --> 00:42:17.103
that are being fed into some equations, but you can actually interact with them like poke

00:42:17.103 --> 00:42:20.384
and prod and see what happens if you change this.

00:42:20.384 --> 00:42:24.823
And like, I want that not just for, let's say, some parameters that somebody might expose

00:42:24.823 --> 00:42:28.744
in a simulation or in a model, but like, what if I edit the code?

00:42:28.744 --> 00:42:33.624
Like going back to that kind of view source mentality where I can see how things are built

00:42:33.624 --> 00:42:38.064
and like, what happens if I comment out this line or if I change this to that, you know,

00:42:38.064 --> 00:42:39.503
and be able to tinker with it?

00:42:39.503 --> 00:42:44.024
There's something fun about these documents that you — that other people have created,

00:42:44.183 --> 00:42:47.543
that are then more interpretable and editable even by you.

00:42:47.543 --> 00:42:51.543
Yeah, it feels like something about like — there's something around like owning the means of

00:42:51.543 --> 00:42:52.543
production.

00:42:52.543 --> 00:43:00.223
I found it really interesting, like I — like the R community never really used notebooks.

00:43:00.223 --> 00:43:03.544
I think partly because we always had this interactive REPL, like that's where you do

00:43:03.544 --> 00:43:08.944
your kind of learning and iteration, and then you record what you found in an R Markdown

00:43:08.944 --> 00:43:15.104
recorder doc, which you then like render as a whole, like guaranteeing like reproducibility

00:43:15.104 --> 00:43:18.184
because you're running the whole thing from scratch each time.

00:43:18.184 --> 00:43:23.143
The thing I'm finding really interesting is with — like it does feel like AI agents change

00:43:23.143 --> 00:43:26.824
the game a bit because now you want not just the code — you don't want to just give the

00:43:26.824 --> 00:43:30.104
agent the code, but also the output of the code.

00:43:30.104 --> 00:43:33.143
And that's — that seems really, really compelling.

00:43:33.143 --> 00:43:34.143
Yes.

00:43:34.143 --> 00:43:37.143
So that's actually the centerpiece of the new AI that we're working on, which we haven't

00:43:37.343 --> 00:43:42.263
launched kind of to the web yet, but we did soft launch it yesterday to Observable Desktop,

00:43:42.263 --> 00:43:44.184
which is our like desktop app.

00:43:44.184 --> 00:43:47.544
But yeah, the key thing is that it does runtime inspection.

00:43:47.544 --> 00:43:51.623
So when you ask the agent to do something and, you know, it generates a bunch of code

00:43:51.623 --> 00:43:56.184
or whatever, it doesn't just assume that that code did exactly what it expected.

00:43:56.184 --> 00:44:01.384
Like it can actually inspect any of the declared top-level variables, as well as anything that

00:44:01.384 --> 00:44:06.203
was displayed, and it really changes the behavior of the agent.

00:44:06.263 --> 00:44:09.684
So like one of the examples that I like to do — because it has all this innate knowledge,

00:44:09.684 --> 00:44:10.684
right?

00:44:10.684 --> 00:44:12.283
Like it knows the Penguin's dataset.

00:44:12.283 --> 00:44:17.084
But the funny thing is the Penguin's dataset, sometimes it's called BillLengthMM, and sometimes

00:44:17.084 --> 00:44:21.604
it's CullmanLengthMM, which is like a more technical name for the bridge of the bill.

00:44:21.604 --> 00:44:23.884
And the one in Observable uses CullmanLength.

00:44:23.884 --> 00:44:28.324
So I like to do this — kind of like I like to deliberately mislead the agent, and I ask

00:44:28.324 --> 00:44:31.563
it to make a chart of Penguin BillLengthMM.

00:44:31.563 --> 00:44:33.643
And so it's like, sure, here you go.

00:44:33.643 --> 00:44:38.444
And prior to the inspection, it would like make an empty chart for you, because that

00:44:38.444 --> 00:44:40.164
doesn't exist in the dataset.

00:44:40.164 --> 00:44:43.283
But it would be like, perfect, you know, here's your chart, and the Adelies are like this

00:44:43.283 --> 00:44:44.643
or whatever.

00:44:44.643 --> 00:44:47.923
And because it can't see that it screwed up.

00:44:47.923 --> 00:44:52.464
But now that it can inspect it, it notices that like, hey, there's something missing

00:44:52.464 --> 00:44:53.923
here from this chart.

00:44:53.923 --> 00:44:57.684
And it then goes and like inspects the dataset and says, oh, wait a second, like this has

00:44:57.684 --> 00:44:59.923
different columns than I expected.

00:44:59.923 --> 00:45:02.804
And then it goes ahead and does the correct chart.

00:45:02.964 --> 00:45:06.804
And there's so many other examples like this where, you know, it's working with some dataset

00:45:06.804 --> 00:45:09.883
and it's just slightly different than it expected.

00:45:09.883 --> 00:45:14.483
And the fact that it can actually verify that and then correct for it makes it much more

00:45:14.483 --> 00:45:15.483
robust.

00:45:15.483 --> 00:45:19.363
Have you seen our BluffBench?

00:45:19.363 --> 00:45:24.603
Simon Couch and Sarah Altman did this for us, where we kind of noticed like, the LLMs

00:45:24.603 --> 00:45:26.804
are like pretty lazy at reading the plots.

00:45:26.804 --> 00:45:31.524
And often they'll just effectively like read the axis labels and then based on the kind

00:45:31.524 --> 00:45:36.483
of like if you do a plot of fuel economy and then ask it like what's going on, it just

00:45:36.483 --> 00:45:41.443
tells you the expected relationship between engine size and fuel economy without actually

00:45:41.443 --> 00:45:43.163
looking at the plot.

00:45:43.163 --> 00:45:46.483
It can be very dangerous because it has that kind of innate understanding.

00:45:46.483 --> 00:45:52.004
And also I think they tend to be too optimistic in a sense where like either is you wrote

00:45:52.004 --> 00:45:55.323
the code and it assumes you know what you're doing or it wrote the code and it assumes

00:45:55.323 --> 00:45:57.483
it knows what it's doing.

00:45:57.483 --> 00:46:02.084
And so yeah, you do have to kind of nudge it to be a little bit more discerning in looking

00:46:02.084 --> 00:46:06.084
at that output because we found that even when it could see the output, like if we didn't

00:46:06.084 --> 00:46:10.004
tell it that it really needed to review it and make sure that it did what it expected,

00:46:10.004 --> 00:46:11.284
it wouldn't do well.

00:46:11.284 --> 00:46:15.244
And then similarly, so one of the big challenges with runtime inspection, particularly working

00:46:15.244 --> 00:46:18.443
with data, is you have large datasets, right?

00:46:18.443 --> 00:46:22.724
So you have, you know, hundreds of megabytes or even more of datasets you might have loaded

00:46:22.724 --> 00:46:23.724
into memory.

00:46:23.724 --> 00:46:26.643
Obviously, you can't fit that entire thing into the context.

00:46:26.804 --> 00:46:31.483
And even for an SVG, like if you have lots and lots of circles or lines or whatever,

00:46:31.483 --> 00:46:33.923
like that can be many kilobytes as well.

00:46:33.923 --> 00:46:40.163
And so we've written some kind of interesting code to inspect those arbitrary values that

00:46:40.163 --> 00:46:45.244
hopefully does a good job of kind of giving it a broad overview, like deep enough that

00:46:45.244 --> 00:46:49.203
it can kind of see some examples but not see everything.

00:46:49.203 --> 00:46:54.804
But you also have to tell it like whether or not it's truncated.

00:46:54.804 --> 00:46:59.284
Because, you know, if it thinks that that might be truncated, it'll just assume everything's

00:46:59.284 --> 00:47:00.284
fine.

00:47:00.284 --> 00:47:01.284
It's like, oh, everything's fine.

00:47:01.284 --> 00:47:04.844
I just can't see anything, you know, but it's like you have to tell it what it's looking

00:47:04.844 --> 00:47:08.564
at and tell it to be more discerning.

00:47:08.564 --> 00:47:15.004
And have you all had to dig a lot into like evals, whether with a capital E or lowercase

00:47:15.004 --> 00:47:22.004
E, like if you change the software, the prompts, how does the agent's behavior change?

00:47:22.004 --> 00:47:23.004
Yeah, very much.

00:47:23.203 --> 00:47:26.443
In a way, that's like a flashback to what I was talking about earlier, working on search

00:47:26.443 --> 00:47:27.443
quality.

00:47:27.443 --> 00:47:28.443
The Google eval.

00:47:28.443 --> 00:47:29.443
Yeah.

00:47:29.443 --> 00:47:32.763
No, for sure that we have like these eval suites that we run.

00:47:32.763 --> 00:47:39.203
I think, you know, they are helpful, but we need a lot more in a sense, like, you know,

00:47:39.203 --> 00:47:42.823
and we need, as I said, we just like soft launched it yesterday.

00:47:42.823 --> 00:47:47.163
So like more people using it, I think we'll hopefully get feedback from real users who

00:47:47.163 --> 00:47:50.423
share their work with us and kind of get feedback that way.

00:47:50.423 --> 00:47:51.423
But I think you're right.

00:47:51.423 --> 00:47:56.064
You like you need some way of knowing when you make a change to your harness or to the

00:47:56.064 --> 00:47:59.744
prompts or whatever, like what is the actual effect of that?

00:47:59.744 --> 00:48:03.464
And if you don't have the evals, then you're basically going blind, like whatever you're

00:48:03.464 --> 00:48:04.784
testing manually.

00:48:04.784 --> 00:48:06.263
Maybe that works great.

00:48:06.263 --> 00:48:09.744
But all these other things that people will encounter once you make that change, you're

00:48:09.744 --> 00:48:12.143
not aware of those changes that you're making.

00:48:12.143 --> 00:48:17.124
It is very like that's the most, I think, frustrating thing about working on agents

00:48:17.203 --> 00:48:21.804
is just nobody really understands how they work or what you should be doing or like you

00:48:21.804 --> 00:48:25.564
would change one thing and who knows what the effect is going to be.

00:48:25.564 --> 00:48:28.443
So if you don't have evals, you're really operating blind.

00:48:28.443 --> 00:48:29.443
Yeah.

00:48:29.443 --> 00:48:33.483
I do appreciate, though, that the Palmer's Penguins dataset is doing its part, like playing

00:48:33.483 --> 00:48:40.363
it's, you know, it's doing its part in making sure the agents do their job well.

00:48:40.363 --> 00:48:41.363
Yeah.

00:48:41.363 --> 00:48:44.323
It's really hard to write good evals as well, we've discovered.

00:48:44.323 --> 00:48:49.363
So, you know, you have these different, I mean, first of all, even if you set the temperature

00:48:49.363 --> 00:48:54.763
to zero, like it still does change, I mean, you know, like your system prompt includes

00:48:54.763 --> 00:48:56.043
the current date in it.

00:48:56.043 --> 00:48:58.763
So that's like one way that things can be different.

00:48:58.763 --> 00:49:03.443
But who knows, like what the other underlying instabilities are in there.

00:49:03.443 --> 00:49:08.663
But the challenges with writing the evals are basically like how specific are your assertions

00:49:08.663 --> 00:49:11.363
and how specific are your prompts?

00:49:11.404 --> 00:49:14.964
Because when you have failures, you know, your choices are like, do I make my assertions

00:49:14.964 --> 00:49:15.964
more general?

00:49:15.964 --> 00:49:19.363
Like basically, do I enumerate more and more of the various things that I've seen that

00:49:19.363 --> 00:49:20.363
are acceptable?

00:49:20.363 --> 00:49:24.004
Or do I somehow like try to make them more general?

00:49:24.004 --> 00:49:28.003
Or do I kind of change the prompt and make the prompt much more specific?

00:49:28.003 --> 00:49:32.284
So like one of the examples that we run into is that the agent is just like happily keeps

00:49:32.284 --> 00:49:35.484
going, you know, like it just keeps showing you more and more things.

00:49:35.484 --> 00:49:39.924
If you ask it kind of too open-ended a question, it can easily run for, you know, a few minutes

00:49:39.924 --> 00:49:42.904
or whatever, generating different views and stuff like that.

00:49:42.904 --> 00:49:47.524
And so if you want to have an eval that runs efficiently and has like a 30 second timeout

00:49:47.524 --> 00:49:51.443
or something like that, you do have to be a little bit more specific to tell the agent

00:49:51.443 --> 00:49:57.524
to kind of wrap it up and be concise in its response.

00:49:57.524 --> 00:50:03.104
But of course, the danger is that if you are too specific in your prompts, then they're

00:50:03.104 --> 00:50:06.484
no longer kind of representative of what users will do.

00:50:06.484 --> 00:50:11.284
And so again, having that external feedback, like having real users using it, is essential

00:50:11.284 --> 00:50:16.364
to know whether your evals are really representative of actual usage or not.

00:50:16.364 --> 00:50:18.164
Yeah, that makes sense.

00:50:18.164 --> 00:50:21.524
And I know you also, oh, did you have a, you sure?

00:50:21.524 --> 00:50:22.524
Yeah.

00:50:22.524 --> 00:50:23.524
All right.

00:50:23.524 --> 00:50:25.724
Last chance, you know.

00:50:25.724 --> 00:50:31.044
I know this might also tie into, I saw you wrote a blog post on playing safely with fire

00:50:31.044 --> 00:50:32.044
last year.

00:50:32.044 --> 00:50:33.044
Yeah.

00:50:34.044 --> 00:50:35.044
I'd be curious to hear.

00:50:35.044 --> 00:50:36.044
Which is about AI, by the way.

00:50:36.044 --> 00:50:37.044
Yeah, sorry.

00:50:37.044 --> 00:50:38.044
Not about fire.

00:50:38.044 --> 00:50:39.044
Not actually.

00:50:39.044 --> 00:50:44.924
You wrote this beautiful blog post about arson that really spoke to me.

00:50:44.924 --> 00:50:50.123
I'm curious, you've mentioned so much about evals and this use of agents and notebooks.

00:50:50.123 --> 00:50:53.844
I'd be curious, maybe you could recap a little bit about the blog post.

00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:58.570
and whether any of your thoughts have changed or stayed the same? Because I know so much has

00:50:58.570 --> 00:51:02.170
happened in the last year. Yeah. Well, the main thing is really about interpretability,

00:51:02.730 --> 00:51:05.850
verifiability, and trust. You know, I think

00:51:06.334 --> 00:51:13.134
Certainly, the models, the coding agents, are somewhat miraculous or magic in what they

00:51:13.134 --> 00:51:20.654
can do, but are also clearly capable of misleading you if not lying to you.

00:51:20.654 --> 00:51:23.094
They can be sycophantic.

00:51:23.094 --> 00:51:28.053
They can assume things are working when they're not or just make stuff up and all that sort

00:51:28.053 --> 00:51:29.053
of stuff.

00:51:29.053 --> 00:51:34.954
So I think while they are very exciting as a technology, I think it's easy to be misled

00:51:34.954 --> 00:51:35.954
by them as well.

00:51:35.954 --> 00:51:38.514
And certainly there's a lot of hype around it as well.

00:51:38.514 --> 00:51:42.793
And so I think our take is coming back to that, you know, how do we make it a more human

00:51:42.793 --> 00:51:46.113
medium for computation, for programming?

00:51:46.113 --> 00:51:50.714
And so if we're incorporating AI into that, it has to be about how does a human understand

00:51:50.714 --> 00:51:54.314
what the agent is doing and how do we make it more verifiable?

00:51:54.314 --> 00:51:59.034
And in a way, a lot of what we're doing now, I think bringing the agents into notebooks

00:51:59.034 --> 00:52:05.753
and kind of having this code-first way of working, is trying to, in a sense, shift some

00:52:05.753 --> 00:52:12.194
of the agent thinking into code, because that is a more formal specification, a more verifiable

00:52:12.194 --> 00:52:13.194
specification.

00:52:13.194 --> 00:52:19.113
So I have this kind of saying where the agent can lie to you with text, but it can't lie

00:52:19.113 --> 00:52:21.033
to you with code.

00:52:21.033 --> 00:52:24.914
In the sense of, you know, if you ask it something, you're like, what are my top customers or

00:52:24.914 --> 00:52:25.914
something like that?

00:52:25.914 --> 00:52:27.514
And it just gives you a markdown bullet list.

00:52:27.514 --> 00:52:28.874
You know, who knows if that's right?

00:52:29.713 --> 00:52:33.594
You need to cross-reference it with an actual query in order to know whether that's correct.

00:52:33.594 --> 00:52:37.634
If it gives you code, you have the problem of whether or not the code is relevant.

00:52:37.634 --> 00:52:42.314
But assuming that the code runs and is relevant to the question, you can generally trust that

00:52:42.314 --> 00:52:47.514
the query will behave deterministically, kind of give you the results that you expect.

00:52:47.514 --> 00:52:51.594
And so in that sense, we're trying to get the agent to shift more of its thinking to

00:52:51.594 --> 00:52:52.594
code.

00:52:52.594 --> 00:52:57.874
Hopefully that code is still interpretable, but that way it's more verifiable and trustworthy

00:52:57.874 --> 00:52:58.874
and reproducible.

00:52:58.874 --> 00:53:05.274
I heard the idea of the, you know, agents enable like code backed data science nowadays

00:53:05.274 --> 00:53:10.154
where it really is your source of truth and being able to use them more effectively than

00:53:10.154 --> 00:53:16.513
just some sort of markdown list, like you said, and being able to really verify that

00:53:16.513 --> 00:53:17.513
this is correct.

00:53:17.513 --> 00:53:18.513
This is what we want.

00:53:18.513 --> 00:53:22.473
I think it's really powerful in a world where it feels maybe uncertain, you know, where

00:53:22.473 --> 00:53:23.473
is code going?

00:53:23.473 --> 00:53:24.473
But having that as a source of truth.

00:53:24.473 --> 00:53:25.473
Yeah, absolutely.

00:53:25.473 --> 00:53:28.714
It's interesting, you know, because there was this whole like no code, low code movement

00:53:28.714 --> 00:53:34.274
before and I think we were on the peripheral of that working on kind of UI cells and notebooks

00:53:34.274 --> 00:53:35.274
and stuff like that.

00:53:35.274 --> 00:53:41.313
And I think in a way it's liberating to come back to code as like this sure foundation,

00:53:41.313 --> 00:53:44.593
like this reliable thing, this powerful expressive thing.

00:53:44.593 --> 00:53:48.753
And now we're much more specifically focused on, okay, we're not hiding the code or taking

00:53:48.753 --> 00:53:53.554
away the code or abstracting the code, but how can we help people learn how to do that

00:53:53.554 --> 00:53:54.554
code?

00:53:54.634 --> 00:53:58.654
And I think there is a difference between writing code and reading code, like in terms

00:53:58.654 --> 00:54:01.554
of the challenge, the barrier to entry there.

00:54:01.554 --> 00:54:06.953
And so I think, you know, even if you can't write code, if we can teach you to read code

00:54:06.953 --> 00:54:11.554
and review code, you know, that broadens the audience of who can do this.

00:54:11.554 --> 00:54:18.914
I think it does feel like tremendously cool for us that have been trying to like persuade

00:54:18.914 --> 00:54:21.953
people about the magic of code for like so long.

00:54:21.953 --> 00:54:27.313
And now it's like easier than ever for anyone to like access it, which is like really like

00:54:27.313 --> 00:54:30.113
genuinely cool and enabling and democratizing.

00:54:30.113 --> 00:54:31.113
Yeah, absolutely.

00:54:31.113 --> 00:54:35.634
I think that's the most exciting aspect of it because it's not, I think my hope is that

00:54:35.634 --> 00:54:39.673
people don't just purely rely on the agent to do all of the work.

00:54:39.673 --> 00:54:43.274
Like if it helps them get over that initial hurdle and then they're like, oh, if I learn

00:54:43.274 --> 00:54:47.714
a little bit more about how this is working, then I can get more hands on here.

00:54:47.714 --> 00:54:52.434
And it really, you know, helps you kind of scale up your expertise.

00:54:52.434 --> 00:54:57.113
I do think the other thing that I just find really cool is now you can interact with an

00:54:57.113 --> 00:55:02.434
agent in like any human language and like it speaks back to you in your language.

00:55:02.434 --> 00:55:04.473
And I think that's also like really cool.

00:55:04.473 --> 00:55:07.753
Like we never would have been able to like translate all of the documentation, all of

00:55:07.753 --> 00:55:10.274
the UI and all of these different languages.

00:55:10.274 --> 00:55:15.233
But now, you know, it's the translation's not perfect, but just again, like tremendously

00:55:15.233 --> 00:55:17.354
enabling for people.

00:55:17.994 --> 00:55:18.994
Interesting.

00:55:18.994 --> 00:55:23.233
Like as a tool builder, does this change how we're building tools?

00:55:23.233 --> 00:55:27.154
Does it make it feel like we want to have them be more readable, like maybe more scrutinous

00:55:27.154 --> 00:55:31.733
of the APIs that we're writing as people are just looking at this maybe from a slightly

00:55:31.733 --> 00:55:33.274
more outside point of view?

00:55:33.274 --> 00:55:37.733
Yeah, I think that's a really, really interesting question about how we design the agents and

00:55:37.733 --> 00:55:42.413
how we kind of guide them to do certain types of code or certain libraries.

00:55:42.413 --> 00:55:48.814
So most top of mind for us is kind of when you're asking the agent to do a visualization,

00:55:48.814 --> 00:55:52.573
you know, is it going to use D3 or is it going to use plot?

00:55:52.573 --> 00:55:58.034
In general, we very much try to bias it towards plot because plot is a higher level abstraction

00:55:58.034 --> 00:56:00.613
like grammar of graphics.

00:56:00.613 --> 00:56:04.254
It is, you know, there are certain things that you can't really do in plot, at least

00:56:04.254 --> 00:56:05.254
not yet.

00:56:05.254 --> 00:56:07.573
Like there's no tree maps in plot, for example.

00:56:07.573 --> 00:56:10.974
And so there are certain things that you do need to use D3 to use those.

00:56:10.974 --> 00:56:15.334
But in general, we try to bias it towards plot because if it is able to use plot, it's

00:56:15.334 --> 00:56:20.613
much more likely to produce a good output, a correct, like non-buggy, but also just a

00:56:20.613 --> 00:56:22.054
better designed output.

00:56:22.054 --> 00:56:25.534
Like they look better, they have better tooltips that are built in, they kind of make better

00:56:25.534 --> 00:56:28.374
choices by default and all that sort of thing.

00:56:28.374 --> 00:56:34.113
So I think it is important still the design of these abstractions, designs of those libraries.

00:56:34.113 --> 00:56:39.054
It's not like it can use D3 to do all of the things that you can do in plot.

00:56:39.133 --> 00:56:44.334
It's just much harder to get it to produce as good of an output with D3 as it is with

00:56:44.334 --> 00:56:45.573
plot.

00:56:45.573 --> 00:56:51.693
There's also a really good feedback loop in place where you ask it to do something and

00:56:51.693 --> 00:56:53.054
it makes a mistake.

00:56:53.054 --> 00:56:57.413
And then you're like, my choice is I can either change the prompt to teach the AI to do something

00:56:57.413 --> 00:56:59.974
differently, teach the agent to do something differently.

00:56:59.974 --> 00:57:05.293
Or I can go back to plot and add a new feature to plot or add some better defaults or better

00:57:05.293 --> 00:57:07.453
warnings or something like that.

00:57:07.453 --> 00:57:11.774
And it's fun to have that instantaneous feedback where you just, you change the feature, you

00:57:11.774 --> 00:57:15.974
change the library and you can immediately test it against the agent with all these different

00:57:15.974 --> 00:57:16.974
evals.

00:57:16.974 --> 00:57:17.974
And it kind of helps you.

00:57:17.974 --> 00:57:22.853
Yeah, it's another feedback loop to stress test the design of your interfaces.

00:57:22.853 --> 00:57:27.733
Are the agents pretty good at sticking with plot or where does the path of desire go for

00:57:27.733 --> 00:57:28.733
agents?

00:57:28.733 --> 00:57:30.173
Do they want plot or D3?

00:57:30.173 --> 00:57:35.293
I mean, I don't know how much of it is the prompt that we've given it.

00:57:35.293 --> 00:57:39.254
It definitely sticks to plot pretty reliably.

00:57:39.254 --> 00:57:43.733
And I think a big part of that is just the whole like observable community and all the

00:57:43.733 --> 00:57:47.534
public notebooks that have kind of fed into these models, like it really does have a pretty

00:57:47.534 --> 00:57:51.693
good understanding of both how D3 works and how plot works.

00:57:51.693 --> 00:57:55.173
But of course, we've given it instruction recommending the use of plot for most of its

00:57:55.173 --> 00:57:57.054
visualization work.

00:57:57.054 --> 00:58:03.173
And that kind of for the more advanced stuff, you know, the tree maps, as I mentioned, or

00:58:03.334 --> 00:58:07.133
some of the more like animations that'll use D3 for that.

00:58:07.133 --> 00:58:12.334
Because the other obvious advantage of plot is like it's easier for humans to read that

00:58:12.334 --> 00:58:16.314
rather than trying to fully understand what the D3 code is.

00:58:16.314 --> 00:58:17.374
And that's part of our goal.

00:58:17.374 --> 00:58:21.814
Like I want it to produce something that is interpretable and kind of teaches you how

00:58:21.814 --> 00:58:26.413
to use plot and kind of because you're going to want to do that refinement as well, right?

00:58:26.413 --> 00:58:30.453
So if you are looking at the output of a chart, but if you can see what the specification

00:58:30.453 --> 00:58:34.133
is, that might give you some hints as to how to guide the agent when you want to refine

00:58:34.133 --> 00:58:35.133
it.

00:58:35.133 --> 00:58:40.214
When I think everyone too now has had this experience where you've got like, yeah, the

00:58:40.214 --> 00:58:44.173
AI has produced something that's like 95% what you want.

00:58:44.173 --> 00:58:50.814
And you like ask for one very simple thing to get it to 100% and it like makes it worse.

00:58:50.814 --> 00:58:55.834
And you just get like stuck in that, like trying to prompt it to do the right thing.

00:58:55.834 --> 00:58:59.013
But often like when the code's right there, you're like, okay, we'll just change that.

00:58:59.573 --> 00:59:00.573
That's easy.

00:59:00.573 --> 00:59:01.573
Like it's explicit.

00:59:01.573 --> 00:59:07.654
I don't get stuck in this like really frustrating loop where the agent just seems so dumb.

00:59:07.654 --> 00:59:11.214
So we have some cool stuff that we haven't announced yet, but it's reminding me of it.

00:59:11.214 --> 00:59:16.893
And basically what we're working on is kind of like a REPL compliment to a notebook.

00:59:16.893 --> 00:59:21.853
And the idea is that the REPL, which is actually, we call it chat, is basically like an agent

00:59:21.853 --> 00:59:25.613
first way of developing with it, where you're kind of, all of your messages are going to

00:59:25.613 --> 00:59:30.893
the agent and the agent is like replying with live code that runs in the chat.

00:59:30.893 --> 00:59:36.254
And it's great for experimentation and kind of ideation.

00:59:36.254 --> 00:59:41.133
You don't have to worry about it kind of destroying things because it can only add to the conversation.

00:59:41.133 --> 00:59:44.294
And it clearly puts the emphasis on like, just ask it questions.

00:59:44.294 --> 00:59:48.654
Like it's not the same as it's much less intimidating than opening up a notebook where like the

00:59:48.654 --> 00:59:52.174
first thing you see is a blinking cursor and a code cell and you're like, what even goes

00:59:52.174 --> 00:59:53.174
in here?

00:59:53.174 --> 00:59:57.534
Like, it's just ask a question and the agent will give you an answer.

00:59:57.534 --> 01:00:02.453
But that doesn't kind of scale up to beyond the 95% case.

01:00:02.453 --> 01:00:06.933
Like it's really not good for refinement where you get something that's pretty close, but

01:00:06.933 --> 01:00:10.654
then you could go through like 20 different charts that all get added to the conversation

01:00:10.654 --> 01:00:13.013
and it becomes a mess, it becomes slow.

01:00:13.013 --> 01:00:17.714
And so the way that we've designed it is these chats are actually just a different interface

01:00:17.714 --> 01:00:18.714
for notebooks.

01:00:18.714 --> 01:00:22.933
And so you can transition into a notebook and then you can switch into this refinement

01:00:23.693 --> 01:00:24.693
model.

01:00:24.693 --> 01:00:28.214
And that's what lets you kind of edit in place and hopefully get to that 100% case.

01:00:28.214 --> 01:00:34.053
Yeah, I was thinking about this morning because I was using Gemini to make a logo and it like

01:00:34.053 --> 01:00:38.053
put a white background and I'm like, please make the background transparent.

01:00:38.053 --> 01:00:42.493
And so in the background, it just drew like the white and gray squares, like when you

01:00:42.493 --> 01:00:43.493
often see.

01:00:43.493 --> 01:00:47.294
And I was like, no, like make it transparent, like it just does not.

01:00:47.294 --> 01:00:52.294
And that's just like so intensely frustrating when you're like, you've done this amazing

01:00:52.654 --> 01:00:53.654
job.

01:00:53.654 --> 01:00:55.174
I've given you this really vague, ill-defined thing.

01:00:55.174 --> 01:00:56.373
You've killed it.

01:00:56.373 --> 01:01:00.094
And now I'm asking you for the small concrete change and you like.

01:01:00.952 --> 01:01:03.752
just cannot do it. It's like, it's fascinating. Yeah.

01:01:04.552 --> 01:01:09.352
I love when it tries to bamboozle you through like smoke and mirrors, you know?

01:01:09.352 --> 01:01:09.912
Yeah.

01:01:09.912 --> 01:01:14.232
I figured, one thing I'm really curious about is, we talked a lot about the tools and your

01:01:14.232 --> 01:01:20.072
approaches. I'm really curious about just how you unwind. Like, how do you unwind after a long day?

